aS'American politics has focused endlessly, if inconclusively on health care, on the uninsured, on jobs, on entitlements and on the deficit.'
p38
aS'Fault lines have been drawn between liberals and conservatives, between rich and poor.'
p39
aS'But the intergenerational aspects of these issues have barely figured in the debate.'
p40
aS'One shocking statistic is that 37 percent of those who came of age in this millennium are unemployed.'
p41
aS'When consumers lack the confidence to spend, when businessmen lack the confidence to invest and to higher, it is the young that suffer most.'
p42
aS'The health insurance debate focused on the uninsured.'
p43
aS'But think for a moment about how health insurance is priced.'
p44
aS'Almost everywhere the young pay the same premium as their more illness prone elders.'
p45
aS'A massive subsidy for the old paid for by the young.'
p46
aS'Tens of millions of young people quite reasonably said no thanks to health insurance until the government mandated that they say yes.'
p47
aS"Medicare and Social Security, Granny's benefits are some 35 percent of the federal government -- federal government budget and are projected to increase to 40 percent in the next decade as the baby boomers retire."
p48
aS'Health care costs are running around 16 percent of GNP compared to nine percent in other developed countries.'
p49
aS'And we have no better health outcomes to show for it.'
p50
aS'End of life care, the heroic measures taken in the final three months before a predictable end are around 25 percent of total health expenditures.'
p51
aS"We simply don't have the money to afford the health care system we've got."
p52
aS"When households want to consume something today that it can't pay for or doesn't choose to pay for, it can borrow money and pay it back with interest in the future, or it can borrow money and stiff its creditors through default, repaying debt with pennies on the dollar."
p53
aS"It's no different for governments."
p54
aS"If they won't cut spending, and they won't raise taxes, they can incur debt which the young will pay for with higher taxes later, or they can stiff their creditors through inflation, repaying the debt with devalued currency."
p55
aS"Young people are paying the costs of sluggish growth today, and they'll be paying the costs of profligate government tomorrow."
p56
aS'And neither political party has anything constructive to say.'
p57
aS"The Democrats don't want to cut entitlements, and the Republicans don't want to raise taxes to pay for them."
p58
aS"Perhaps that's why young people vote less than their elders."
p59
aS"Tonight they can make up for that lapse by voting twice, before the debate and after, after they've heard tonight's stellar panelists address the little noticed issues of America's intergenerational divide."
p60
aS"And with that, it's my privilege to turn the evening over to John Donvan and our outstanding group of panelists."
